  Postal and telecommunications services developed rapidly. 
Total turnover in 1993 of the post and telecommunications 
industry was 9.42 billion yuan, an increase of 65.1 percent over 
1992. The mobile telephone business expanded by 190 percent and 
paging business by 87.2 percent. The number of telephone 
subscribers in urban and rural areas increased by 1.05 million 
in 1993, up 51 percent and accounting for 33.8 percent of total 
telephone users. 
<H5>  5. Domestic Commerce and Prices </H5>
  Domestic consumer goods markets were brisk. Total retail 
sales across society were 140.26 billion yuan, up 32.3 percent 
over the 1992 figure and an increase of 11.9 percent in real 
terms. Retail sale of consumer goods stood at 131.646 billion 
yuan, an increase of 33.8 percent. Of the total 131.646 billion 
yuan, 95.506 billion was consumed in urban areas, an increase of 
40.5 percent, and 36.14 billion in rural areas, up 18.8 percent. 
  Retail sale of food registered mixed results. Sales of eggs 
rose 38.8 percent, sugar 23.7 percent, aquatic products 6.7 
percent, and pork 2.6 percent, while sales of grain and 
vegetable oil declined by 11.4 percent and 17.5 percent 
respectively. Sales of cloth and clothing rose simultaneously, 
the former increasing by 166.1 percent and the latter by 40.3 
percent. Sales of durable consumer goods increased by a big 
margin except for electric fans, whose sales fell a little. 
Sales of color television sets, audio recorders, washing 
machines and refrigerators increased by 38, 45.8, 38.5, and 
36.1 percent respectively. State commercial enterprises greatly 
improved their economic efficiency through transforming their 
managerial mechanisms, and large and medium state enterprises 
increased their vitality. 
  Capital goods markets were brisk. In 1993, materials supply 
and marketing enterprises province wide purchased 58.569 billion 
yuan worth of capital goods, an increase of 31.4 percent on the 
previous year, and their sales totaled 61.052 billion yuan, up 
30.5 percent. Retail sales of capital goods for agricultural use 
in 1993 hit 8.614 billion yuan, an increase of 13 percent over 
the 1992 figure. 
  Price reform deepened. In 1993, apart from adjusting the 
prices of those items specified by the central government, 
Guangdong raised charges for tuition, medical care, public 
services in urban areas, water transport, and electricity, 
giving a bigger role to the needs of the market. Nevertheless, 
affected by excessive social needs and natural disasters, the 
cost of living price index rose by a relatively big margin and 
there was a rather sharp rise in building materials prices and 
service charges. 


