<H5>  6. Foreign Economic Activity </H5>
  The foreign trade volume increased. According to statistics 
released by customs, Guangdong's 1993 foreign trade volume 
totaled $78.344 billion yuan, representing an increase of 19.2 
percent over the previous year. Of the total foreign trade 
volume, the export volume was $37.394 billion, up 11.8 percent, 
and the import volume was $40.95 billion, up 26.8 percent. The 
mix of import and export commodities was further improved. In 
1993, there was a decrease in the amount of traditional primary 
goods sold abroad and a big increase in the amount of imports of 
badly needed raw and semi-finished materials and 
investment-related equipment. 
  A record amount of foreign funds was used. In 1993, a total 
of 19,012 contracts for using foreign funds were signed 
province-wide, up 47.2 percent over the previous year. A total 
of $34.897 billion of foreign funds was contracted, up 75.7 
percent, while actual funds used amounted to $9.652 billion, up 
98.6 percent. Direct investment by foreign businessmen was 
$7.498 billion, up 110 percent. The area of investment was 
expanded. "Foreign-funded" enterprises grew rapidly. By late 
1993, a total of 44,705 foreign-funded enterprises had been 
registered with the relevant authorities, an increase of 69.6 
percent compared with the same period in the previous year. 
  Economic and technological cooperation with foreign 
countries 
presented good prospects. In 1993, a total of 3,706 contracts 
for labor-service cooperation abroad were signed across the 
province, an increase of 10.9 percent over the 1992 figure. The 
contracts involved $262 million, up 11.5 percent, and a turnover 
of $152 million was effected, up 11.8 percent. However, both 
the number of foreign-contracted projects and the effected 
turnover declined [sentence as published]. 
  In 1993, a total of 32.792 million foreign tourists entered 
China through gateways in Guangdong, up 7 percent over the 
previous year. The number of foreign tourists staying overnight 
in guest houses (hotels) catering only to foreign tourists 
reached 6.1219 million, down 11 percent. 
<H5>  7. Finance and Insurance Business </H5>
  In 1993, the departments responsible for financial affairs 
across the province actively carried out the central 
government's measures for improving macro-economic control in 
bringing the financial market out of chaos and rectifying errors 
which had arisen in financial work. In the meantime, they made 
great efforts to encourage bank deposits and used credit funds 
in a reasonable way to provide sufficient funds for key 
projects, for industrial and agricultural production, for 
purchasing agricultural and sideline products, and for some key 
enterprises to help them solve difficulties caused by the short 
supply of circulating funds while keeping financial markets 
stable. 
  In late 1993, outstanding deposits in state banks 
province-wide hit 34.287 billion yuan, up 14.4 percent, of which 
enterprises outstanding deposits were 97.177 billion yuan, an 
increase of 1.586 billion yuan and 1.7 percent, while residents 
in urban and rural areas accounted for 187.451 billion yuan, an 
increase of 41.45 billion yuan and 28.4 percent. Outstanding 
loans granted by banks province-wide totaled 223.734 billion 
yuan, representing an increase of 42.346 billion yuan and 23.4 
percent, of which outstanding revolving credit funds accounted 
for 169.889 billion yuan, up 20.2 percent, and outstanding loans 
for fixed assets accounted for 29.713 billion yuan, up 26 
percent. If the money supply was deducted from that which was 
withdrawn, net money supply in 1993 was 23.58 billion yuan, 
14.425 billion yuan more than in 1992. 
  The insurance business grew at a greater pace. In 1993, 
total underwriting assets amounted to 953.105 billion yuan, an 
increase of 58.8 percent over the previous year. Insurance 
companies province-wide handled a total of 279,400 claims for 
insured assets at home and abroad, paying out a total of 3.293 
billion yuan in damages. In addition, insurance companies paid 
174 million yuan in damages to 192,900 persons. 
<H5>  8. Science and Technology </H5>
  Continued progress was made in science and technology. In 
1993, a total of 185 scientific and technological achievements 
received state and provincial-level awards; of the total, two 
received state invention awards, 15 state scientific and 
technological progress awards, five state "Spark" awards, 129 
provincial scientific and technological awards, 19 provincial 
natural science awards, and 15 provincial "spark" awards. A 
total of 5,020 patent applications were received and 4,546 were 
granted, increases of 7.8 and 170 percent respectively over the 
previous year. Hi-tech industry made bigger progress. By late 
1993, a total of six state-level and three provincial-level 
development zones for industries using high and new technology 
and a hi-tech industrial corridor had been set up across the 
province. A total of 166 enterprises using high and new 
technology and a total of 770 hi-tech products were confirmed as 
reaching relevant standards. 
  The ranks of scientists and technological workers grew and 
more funds were injected into scientific research. In 1993, 
natural and social science and technology personnel working with 
state enterprises and institutions totaled 727,300 (excluding 
personnel from central units stationed in Guangdong), an 
increase of 9.3 percent over the previous year. State 
independent research and development offices totaled 505, while 
scientific research institutes run by colleges and universities 
and large and medium industrial enterprises totaled 362 and 773 
respectively. Scientific and technology people totaled 75,200. 
Expenditure in 1993 on scientific and technological activities 
was 2.168 billion yuan, up 14.7 percent over the previous year. 
  In 1993, there were 50 product quality control offices 
across 
the province. A total of 37 enterprises applied international 
norms to 44 items. Mapping departments drew 3,970 maps of 
various proportions and published 108 commercial maps and books. 
A total of 46 ultra-short-wave weather forecast stations were 
set up across the province. Departments engaged in seismology 
and oceanography research improved their service. 
  Technological markets were brisk. A total of 7,605 
contracts were signed in 1993, involving 1.043 billion yuan, up 
8.5 and 63.2 percent respectively over the previous year. Many 
people showed keen interest in scientific research. Workers 
technological associations across the province solved 4,021 key 
technological problems in production in 1993. 
<H5>  9. Education, Culture, Public Health, Sports </H5>
  The scale of higher education was expanded. In 1993, a total 
of 1,551 research students were recruited province-wide, an 
increase of 21.7 percent over the previous year figure, and the 
number of research students receiving education was 3,983, up 
13.2 percent. Universities and colleges enrolled 47,600 students 
in 1993, up 34.1 percent, and had 117,000 students, up 20.1 
percent. 
  Secondary vocational and technical education continued to 
grow. All types of secondary vocational and technical schools 
had 415,000 students (of which 76,800 were studying in technical 
schools), accounting for 55.6 percent of the total number of 
senior middle school students, an increase of 2.5 percentage 
points over the previous year. 
  More people received compulsory education. In 1993, junior 
middle schools province-wide had 2.4404 million students and 
primary schools 8.3214 million. "Project Hope" made progress 
day by day. The attendance ratio of primary school age 
population reached 99.5 percent, the proportion of primary 
school students entering junior middle schools rose to 88.4 
percent from 86.5 percent in the previous year, and the 
percentage of middle and primary school students discontinuing 
their studies declined. A total of 58 counties (cities, and 
districts) made nine-year compulsory education universal. 
  More adults were admitted to schools. High schools for 
adults had 125,200 students, an increase of 65.4 percent over 
the previous year's figure; secondary special or technical 
schools for adults had 164,300, up 21.7 percent; and middle and 
primary schools for adults 617,400. A total of 39,600 young and 
middle-aged illiterates learned to read and write. 
  Cultural undertakings developed each day. By late 1993, 
there were 125 artistic troupes, 112 cultural centers, 112 
public libraries, 108 museums, and 155 archives in the province. 
In addition, there were 94 radio stations including 12 
medium-wave broadcast transmitting stations and relay stations, 
and 43 television stations, including 28 television transmitting 
stations and relay stations. There were 3,680 film projection 
teams. A total of seven feature films were produced, and 186 
new films (long ones) of all types were distributed. There were 
2.082 billion copies, 208 million volumes, and 348 million 
volumes of newspapers, magazines, and books published 
respectively. Control over cultural markets was strengthened. 
  Steady progress was made in public health. By late 1993, 
hospitals province-wide had 129,300 beds, an increase of 3.6 
percent. Professional health workers totaled 211,900, up 3.3 
percent. Of the total, 90,100 were doctors and 56,200 master 
nurses and nurses, up 4.3 and 5.6 percent respectively. Great 
achievements were made in building commune hospitals in rural 
townships and towns. The hospitals had 36,700 beds and 53,100 
health workers in 1993, up 4.9 and 3.1 percent respectively. 
  Relatively good results were scored in sports. Our athletes 
broke 10 world records, six Asian records, and 42 national 
records, and won 19 world, 39 Asian, and 42 national 
championships. At the Seventh National Games, our athletes 
obtained 31 gold medals and the same number of silver medals 
with the numbers of gold medals and medals and total scores 
ranking second respectively among other provinces and autonomous 
regions. Mass sports activities developed vigorously. A total 
of 9,865 sports meets were held across the province with 1.85 
million people participating in them. 
<H5>  10. Population and People's Lives </H5>
  A sample investigation in 1993 into population changes in 
the 
province showed that the birth rate was 18.34 per thousand, the 
death rate 5.84 per thousand, and the natural growth rate was 
12.5 per thousand. In late 1993, the number of regular 
residents was 65.82 million and the domiciled population was 
66.07 million. 
  Residents' income increased steadily. According to sample 
investigations, in 1993 the average amount of per-capita income 
used for living expenses was 4,277 yuan, up 34.3 percent over 
the previous year and showing an increase of 10.1 percent in 
real terms. The per-capita net income in rural areas was 1,675 
yuan, up 28.1 percent over the 1992 figure and an increase of 
6.1 percent in real terms. 
  Reforms in the labor field were speeded up. In 1993, the 
number of employment agencies at all levels increased to 1,000 
and 482,800 people in urban areas were given jobs. In late 
1993, the unemployment rate was 2.02 percent. By late 1993, a 
total of 5.0241 million workers and 1.1398 retired workers were 
participating in the old-age insurance scheme, representing an 
increase of 14.3 percent over the previous year. By late 1993, 
the number of workers province-wide had increased to 8.8152 
million, including 1.423 million working with private 
enterprises and self-employed laborers in urban areas, 397,800 
more than the 1992 figure. 
  Workers' wages were further raised. The 1993 total amount of 
workers' wages province-wide was 44.427 billion yuan, up 32.8 
percent over the 1992 figure. The per-capita annual wage was 
5,166 yuan, an increase of 5.2 percent in real terms. 
  Living conditions in urban and rural areas were further 
improved. Residential units completed in urban areas in 1993 
measured 21.9589 square meters and 26.8765 square meters in 
rural areas. 
  Social services were further expanded. Convalescent homes 
had 42,900 beds in 1993, up 13.8 percent over the 1992 figure, 
and took in 32,500 patients, up 11.7 percent. Towns and 
townships which have established rural social security networks 
accounted for 57 percent of the total, and all kinds of 
community service facilities in urban areas were further 
improved. 
  Environmental protection was further promoted. A total of 
118 environmental monitoring stations, 37 nature reserves, 168 
smoke and dust control zones, and 48 environmental noise control 
zones were set up across the province. 
Notes: 1. Figures given in this communique are 
preliminary 
statistics. 
  2. Gross domestic product, value added by various 
industries, and total values given in this communique are 
calculated at current prices and growth rates in comparable 
prices. 
  3. The base figures for all the above indexes are based 
on statistics in the 1993 Guangdong Statistical 
Yearbook. 

